               <msContents>
                  <summary>An abridged selection of poems from the <title>Dīvān</title> by the
                     influential Timurid-era poet Amīr Shāhī Sabzavārī (d. 1453). Probably completed
                     in late 15th to early 16th-century Iran, the volume bears delicate
                     spray-painted stencilled margins and headers throughout.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_249-item1">
                     <author key="person_26536597" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/26536597/">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied">Amīr Shāhī</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20641">Dīvān-i Amīr Shāhī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_20641">دیوان امیر شاهی</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus> یا
                        رب بسوز سینۀ رندان باک باز</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="102b" to="102b"> برگ ۱۰۲پ (folio
                           102b):</locus> سخن تا چند گویم پیچ در پیچ * ترا من دوست میدارم دیگر
                        هیچ</explicit>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <colophon>No colophon</colophon>
                     <note>Michael Kerney notes that in comparison to most versions, this volume
                        lacks roughly half the usual contents. The incipit matches Bodleian <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_22899"><idno>MS.
                              Selden superius 98</idno></ref>; see Sachau and Ethé.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Various coloured and stencilled <material>paper</material> probably
                           manufactured in <placeName cert="medium"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/149669363">Iran</placeName>.</support>
                        <extent><measure type="folio" quantity="103">103 folios, 4 flyleaves (ff. ii
                              + 103 + ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>171</height>
                              <width>96</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>102</height>
                              <width>55</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>Foliated in pencilled Arabic numerals on the upper left corners
                           by the cataloguer.</foliation>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In poor condition. Extensive insect damage
                           throughout. Folios <locus from="18" to="18">18</locus>, <locus from="35"
                              to="35">35</locus>, <locus from="42" to="42">42</locus>, <locus
                              from="57" to="57">57</locus>, <locus from="62" to="62">62</locus>,
                              <locus from="74" to="75">74–75</locus>, and <locus from="94" to="95"
                              >94–95</locus> spattered with corrosive verdigris (copper acetate)
                           that severely weakened and embrittled the paper, with overly-rigid
                           historical repairs causing further stress and damage. Rigidly-tipped
                           endpapers stress the gutter margins of the first and final
                           folios.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="8" n="mistara">Written in 1 column, with 8
                           lines. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink"/>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="marginal">Spray-painted stencilled designs throughout,
                        including foliate arabesque headings and triangles adjacent to oblique
                        lines, as well as decorative margins— especially of central quire
                        double-page bifolia— with ducks, doves, deer, and cloud bands. Other margins
                        masked and the central text areas finely sprayed in in pink and red, or
                        vice-versa. Marginal ruling in <material>gold</material>, outlined in
                           <material>black</material>. <p>Folios <locus from="18" to="18"
                           >18</locus>, <locus from="35" to="35">35</locus>, <locus from="42"
                              to="42">42</locus>, <locus from="57" to="57">57</locus>, <locus
                              from="62" to="62">62</locus>, <locus from="74" to="75">74–75</locus>,
                           and <locus from="94" to="95">94–95</locus> spattered with corrosive
                           verdigris (copper acetate), now severely degraded.</p>
                        <p>Headings and added verses on folios <locus from="59a" to="59a"
                              >59a</locus> and <locus from="86b" to="86b">86b</locus> subsequently
                           overpainted in <material>red</material>.</p>
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions><lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list rend="bulleted">
                        <item>Marginalia on folios <locus from="40b" to="40b">40b</locus>, <locus
                              from="63a" to="63a">63a</locus>, and <locus from="80b" to="80b"
                              >80b</locus>.</item>
                        <item><locus from="right_paste-down" to="right_paste-down"> right
                              paste-down</locus> top, <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Diwan
                           Shahi</q></item>
                        <item>Also inscribed on the <locus from="right_paste-down"
                              to="right_paste-down"> right paste-down</locus>, unsigned, but very
                           likely in the hand of <persName role="fmo ins" cert="medium"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962" key="person_44733962">Sir Gore
                              Ouseley</persName>: <q xml:lang="en">A collection of amatorial Poems
                              by Shahi, a persian Poet. There is a Turkish commentary upon these
                              poems among the Laudian MSS in the Bodleian Library of Oxford</q>
                           along with <q xml:lang="en">No. 55</q> at the bottom (however, this does
                           not appear to comport to the volume that he describes in his
                              <title>Biographical Notices</title>).</item>
                        <item>A pencilled note in another minuscule hand written between the lines
                           of the above: <q xml:lang="en">quoted by De Sacy in his notes to the
                              Pandnameh of Attar, 307, 309.</q></item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="103a" to="103a">103a</locus> inscribed with lines
                           by <persName type="standard" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/16602675/"
                              key="person_16602675">Qāsim Anvār (1356–1433)</persName> in shikastah
                           script.</item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="103b" to="103b">103b</locus> bears an unidentified
                           couplet written vertically in nasta‘līq script.</item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left paste-down,</locus>
                     <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with shelfmark <q xml:lang="en"
                        >F/9</q>, and <q xml:lang="en">Bland MSS No. 469.</q>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1500" notAfter="1700">
                        <p> Covered in full, polished black, very fine-grained probably calfskin
                              <material>leather</material>, over thin
                              <material>pasteboard</material> with fore-edge and envelope flap
                           (hence type II binding per Déroche, with flap), with minimal insect
                           damage. Repairs to the <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and
                              <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus> edges and fore-edge of the
                           right board in thinned black goatskin <material>leather</material>, with
                           heavier patches applied to the <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus>
                           and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus> of the spine. Thick,
                           bone-coloured European wove endpapers. Envelope flap interior lined with
                           the same goatskin <material>leather</material>used for exterior repairs. </p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><p>Boards stamped with central mandorlas with
                              floriate arabesque scrollwork and a smaller medallion featuring a
                              lotus design upon the envelope flap exterior. Once repaired, a binder
                              titled the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> at the head in
                                 <material>gold</material> with handle letters <q xml:lang="en"
                                 >Diwan Shahi M.S.</q> Further decorated with thin and thick blind
                              fillet lines on the boards, with centring marks adjacent to the
                              blocked impressions, and vertical blind fillet lines on the fore-edge
                              flap.</p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>172</height>
                              <width>105</width>
                              <depth>18</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>handle with caution. In fair condition. The binding separates
                           from the text block.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <decoNote type="stamp">
                        <p>Impressed on folio <locus from="103a" to="103a"/> small, circular,
                           partially-legible namesake seal intaglio-carved in nasta‘līq script in
                           two stacked lines in the centre, impressed in black ink bearing a pious
                           Arabic formula that invokes the family of the Prophet, which indicates
                           the name of former owner or associate <persName type="standard"
                              cert="medium" role="fmo seal" key="person_f6558">Muḥammad
                              Muṣṭafá</persName>:</p>
                        <p><q xml:lang="fa">(?)آل محمد مصطفی جمعی</q>
                        </p>
                        <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>13</height>
                              <width>15</width>
                           </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin> Probably completed in <origPlace cert="medium"><country
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/149669363">Iran</country></origPlace>, in the
                        <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1450" notAfter="1600">late 15th
                        to 16th century</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Impressed with a namesake seal of a former owner or associate named
                           <persName type="standard" role="fmo seal" key="person_f6558">Muḥammad
                           Muṣṭafá</persName></p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>While unsigned, an inscription on <locus from="right_paste-down"
                           to="right_paste-down"> right paste-down</locus> appears to comport with
                        the hand of <persName role="fmo ins" cert="medium"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962" key="person_44733962">Sir Gore
                           Ouseley (1770–1844)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by scholar <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923"
                           >Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose death <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> antiquarian bookseller <persName type="standard"
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225"
                           >Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to
                        in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date> to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                        >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                        Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
